    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "Hey, I'm looking at some Cessna maintenance docs. Can you explain the actual physics of how a pitot tube works to measure airspeed? Also, why is it such a big deal if the opening gets blocked?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "The pitot tube, a crucial component in aircraft airspeed measurement, operates on the principle of Bernoulli's principle, which states that an increase in airspeed results in a decrease in air pressure. The pitot tube is essentially a tube that directs air from the surrounding environment into a pressure-sensitive chamber, where it's compared to the static air pressure. The difference in pressure between the two is proportional to the airspeed. If the pitot tube is blocked, the airspeed reading will be grossly inaccurate, as the blocked pitot tube will not be able to measure the actual airspeed, leading to a false reading. This is a critical safety issue, as pilots rely on accurate airspeed data to control the aircraft's speed and altitude.",
